methods were compared and tested for their relative accuracty. Finally, marten ectoparasites were surveyed and the role of the fleas (Siphonaptera) in the transmission of plague (Yersinia pestis) to martens was explored.</para></abstract><keywordSet><keyword keywordType="place">Sagehen Creek Basin</keyword><keywordThesaurus>None</keywordThesaurus></keywordSet><keywordSet><keyword keywordType="taxonomic">Sierran pine marten</keyword><keywordThesaurus>None</keywordThesaurus></keywordSet><keywordSet><keyword keywordType="taxonomic">fleas</keyword><keywordThesaurus>None</keywordThesaurus></keywordSet><keywordSet><keyword keywordType="theme">plague</keyword><keywordThesaurus>None</keywordThesaurus></keywordSet><additionalInfo><para>x</para></additionalInfo><intellectualRights><para>permissions</para></intellectualRights><distribution scope="document"><offline><mediumName>hardcopy</mediumName></offline></distribution><coverage scope="document"><temporalCoverage scope="document"><rangeOfDates><beginDate><calendarDate>1979-06-01</calendarDate></beginDate><endDate><calendarDate>1979-11-01</calendarDate></endDate></rangeOfDates></temporalCoverage><geographicCoverage scope="document"><geographicDescription>This work was conducted in the upper Sagehen Creek drainage, located on the east side of the Sierra Nevada in Nevada County.</geographicDescription><boundingCoordinates><westBoundingCoordinate>-120.2367</westBoundingCoordinate><eastBoundingCoordinate>-120.2367</eastBoundingCoordinate><northBoundingCoordinate>39.4317</northBoundingCoordinate><southBoundingCoordinate>39.4317</southBoundingCoordinate></boundingCoordinates></geographicCoverage><taxonomicCoverage scope="document"><generalTaxonomicCoverage>x</generalTaxonomicCoverage><taxonomicClassification><taxonRankName>Species</taxonRankName><taxonRankValue>Martes americana sierrae</taxonRankValue></taxonomicClassification><taxonomicClassification><taxonRankName>Family</taxonRankName><taxonRankValue>Siphonaptera</taxonRankValue></taxonomicClassification><taxonomicClassification><taxonRankName>Species</taxonRankName><taxonRankValue>Yersinia pestis</taxonRankValue></taxonomicClassification></taxonomicCoverage></coverage><contact scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Jeff</givenName><surName>Brown</surName></individualName><organizationName>Sagehen Creek Field Station</organizationName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>P.O. Box 939/11616 Sagehen Rd.</deliveryPoint><city>Truckee</city><postalCode>96160</postalCode><country>USA</country></address><phone phonetype="voice">(530) 587-4830</phone><phone phonetype="Fax">(530) 582-4031</phone><electronicMailAddress>sagehen@berkeley.edu</electronicMailAddress></contact><methods><methodStep><description><section><title>Methods</title><para>TRAPPING: The study area was divided into 1000, 4 ha cells of the UTM grid. Traps were spaced 200x600m within this grid. Once confined, the marten was immobilized with an intramuscular injection, weighed, measured, and data collected on reproductive condition, molt status, rectal temperature, weather, and habitat. Ectoparasites were collected and preserved, a blood sample was taken to test for bubonic plague antibodies, ear tags were attached, and hair samples were taken.</para><para>TELEMETRY: Six martens were fitted with radio transmitter collars to record activity.</para><para>SCAT COLLECTION: Scats were collected from trapped animals, at frequently used resting sites, while snow-tracking, and along &apos;cubby-hair snare&apos; transects. Scats were then analyzed.</para><para>EMESIS: Induced vomiting was an additional technique used to determine food eaten (in retrospect, this technique was probably inappropriate)</para><para>PREY DISTRIBUTION: 50 randomly located plots were trapped for 3 days each as part of a concurrent vertebrate survey in the study area.</para><para>FEEDING TRIALS: Feeding trials involving a captive ferret were conducted to test for the relationship of prey size to number of scats produced.</para></section></description></methodStep><sampling><studyExtent><description><para>TRAPPING: began in late June and continued through November 1979. 
